  <a href="#1" id="1">
   Workers at KGHM in Lubin, Poland's copper producing combine went on strike yesterday
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   as coal-mining unions staged token stoppages in a third of the country's pits in a major challenge to the government's economic policies.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   The KGHM strike came despite a management offer to increase wages by 20%.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   Coal mining unions are also demanding wage increases as well as a clear restructuring strategy for their industry.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   The copper industry continues to show profit
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   but coal mining is running at a loss.
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   This has led to temporary lay-offs,
  </a>
  <a href="#8" id="8">
   which hit miners' incomes
  </a>
  <a href="#9" id="9">
   and led to the present bout of unrest.
  </a>
